  "why": "The fuzzer enforces naturalness/validity constraints during mutation, but only relative to the immediate parent mutant (i.e., per-step). Algorithm 1 samples inputs from the evolving seed pool S and accepts a mutant only if is_valid(ŝ, s) holds; the is_valid check (from [47]) constrains changed-pixels and maximum pixel change (α, β). Because mutants accepted into S are later re-sampled and further mutated (s = sample(S)), small per-step changes can accumulate across iterations (the paper does not enforce similarity to the original seed nor fix semantically critical content). The authors explicitly measure naturalness (IS/FID) and report that NLC-guided mutations produce more natural images, indicating naturalness is an objective, but the enforcement is per-successive-step rather than preventing cumulative drift. Therefore the design matches the “Medium” description: it enforces naturalness between successive mutation steps without accounting for cumulative distortion across iterations.",
